        {"source": "clarke", "attribution": "Clarke's Commentary", "excerpt": "Death passed upon all men for that (eph' hō) all have sinned — meaning that each individual became a sinner and by that individual sin incurred mortality. The text does not require us to posit the imputation of Adam's guilt to his posterity."},
        {"source": "ellicott", "attribution": "Ellicott's Commentary", "excerpt": "Eph' hō is most naturally rendered 'because,' making 'all sinned' the reason death spread universally. Whether this refers to personal sin, imputed sin, or seminal participation in Adam's act is the question that has divided interpreters from antiquity."}
