        {"source": "ellicott", "attribution": "Ellicott's Commentary", "excerpt": "Adam is a type (τύπος) of the one to come — a figure, a prefigurement, an analogy. The parallel between Adam and Christ is not perfect; Paul is about to show (vv. 15-19) that the gift far exceeds the trespass in every respect."},
        {"source": "barnes", "attribution": "Barnes' Notes", "excerpt": "The reign of death over infants — who had committed no personal act — is Paul's most pointed proof. They died, though they had not sinned after the similitude of Adam's transgression; therefore Adam's sin was the cause of their death."}
